text=(:if authgroup @tas:)%0a%0a(:toggle id=gi show="show grading interface" hide="hide grading interface":)%0a%0a>>id=gi%3c%3c%0a%0a[[GradebookArticles.{$Name}|See article in gradebook]] \\%0a[[{$FullName}?action=diff|See all changes to article]]%0a%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#gradeitem:)%0a%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#gradingcomment:)%0a%0a>>%3c%3c%0a%0a----%0a%0a(:ifend:)%0a%0a[[!LinguisticDiscriminationInTheWild]]%0a%0a!Valley Girls are not stupid%0a%0a:Author: roochis%0a%0a'''Summary:''' \\%0a%0a[[#summary]]%0a%0aDefending "Valley Girl Speak"%0a%0a[[#summaryends]]%0a%0a----%0a[[#content]]%0a%0ahttps://youtu.be/EMnfnD5xcoM %0a%0a^This is a short video making fun of the “Valley Girl Accent”%0a%0aThe description box summarizes it as “Two Valley Girls meet on the street and exhaust their entire vocabulary in under 45 seconds.”%0a%0aThis video heavily implies that women who use a "Valley Girl Accent" are shallow and  unintelligent. %0a%0a“Valley Girl Speak” or “Valley Girl Accent” refers to speech patterns similar to the California Dialect (Valley refers to the San Fernando Valley). This term originally portrayed women who use it as upper-class, shallow, and materialistic. However, today, the phrase “Valley Girl” or “Valley Girl Speak” comes with the implication that the woman who uses it is an airhead. %0a%0aSome characteristics of “Valley Girl Speak” include: %0a%0a- High Rising Terminal (aka up talk) This is when statements have rising intonation, and often, declarative statements sound like questions. %0a%0a- Creaky phonation (aka vocal fry) %0a%0a-Using “like” as a discourse marker (filler word) %0a%0a%0aThe most distinct feature of “Valley Girl Speak” is High Rising Terminal. Surprisingly, this is a phenomenon that has been studied in England, Australia, and New Zealand. Some linguistics believe it originated in the 1950s and others believe it’s centuries old (aka older than the 1980s Valley Girl caricature). Even though “Valley Girl Speak” is almost exclusively used to describe women, men use rising intonation as well. While making simple declarative statements, men and women were found to use rising-intonation similarly. %0a%0aSources: %0a%0ahttps://www.wm.edu/as/sociology/news-events/news-archive/2013-14-archive/overturning.the.myth.of.valley.girl.speack.php%0ahttps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Valley_girl%0a%0a%0a%0a[[#contentends]]%0a----%0a----%0a%0a!!Expansions:%0a[[#expansions]]%0a#foxbegin 210427-040528-551910#%0a(:div1 class=expansionhead:)%0a!!!Let's hope valley girl discrimination is generational %0a-> - angelaw%0a(:div1end:) %0a>>messageitem%3c%3c %0aI think you make some very good points about how valley girl speak and the stereotypes and assumptions associated with it are really just trite and frankly quite tiring. %0aOn the following website, an extremely bothered middle-aged woman writes a very lengthy blog post about just how annoying valley girl accents are and how it makes speakers automatically sound ditzy and materialistic.%0a%0ahttps://chronicfatigue.typepad.com/mj/2012/05/ok-so-like-every-day-on-my-bus-ride-to-work-i-am-like-surrounded-by-these-20-and-30-something-girls-talking-like-rully.html%0a%0aMany linguists have actually studied these trends as you note in your post and one factor brought up was that the heavy discrimination could be because the older generations are less used to hearing these accents. Perhaps this may be the case, but I think in general, the world would be a much better place if we could just stop making assumptions about intelligence based on speaking patterns.  %0a%0asource:https://www.wm.edu/as/sociology/news-events/news-archive/2013-14-archive/overturning.the.myth.of.valley.girl.speack.php%0a>>%3c%3c%0a#foxend 210427-040528-551910#%0a#foxbegin 210508-162703-989280#%0a(:div1 class=expansionhead:)%0a!!!Personal Experiences with Valley Girl Speak %0a-> - dhrutik%0a(:div1end:) %0a>>messageitem%3c%3c %0aI fully agree with the author and the above expansion, particularly that discrimination/assumptions on the basis of something as superficial as speaking patterns are trite and, in this day and age, should be behind us. %0a%0aThe jokes that people make at the expense of "Valley girls" often remind me of the "Dumb blonde" stereotype. Both are used as a means to demean women and make them feel less than for something they can't really control.%0a%0aAs someone from California, I have heard many people surprised to hear that I don't speak in the "Valley girl" way. The kicker is, I actually did live in the Valley until I started grade school. I think there is something interesting in terms of the "Valley girl" modality, particularly with respect to immigrant families and a need to "feel American." %0a%0aMy mom would always tell me that from ages 3-5, whenever we went to family parties with my family that lived further north, near the Bay, my aunts and uncles would always comment on how "American" my accent was. Though I have no recording of myself from this time, I can only imagine that I spoke more like a "Valley girl" than my cousins did, which is what likely contributed to this feeling. Years later, after moving away, when I met people that stayed in the Valley, I found myself thinking the same thing-- that they sounded far more American than I did. It is so disorienting to suddenly question your own American-ness based off of something as simple as a regional accent, but it is a thing and I'm not sure how to quantify it.%0a>>%3c%3c%0a#foxend 210508-162703-989280#%0a[[#expansionsend]]%0a%0a----%0a%25red%25 '''Add an expansion:'''%0a%0a(:if [ exists GradebookExpansions.{$Name}-{$Author} || equal {$Author} {$:Author} ] :)%0a%0a(:else:)%0a%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#newexpansion:)%0a%0a(:ifend:)%0a%0a----%0a----%0a%0a!!Comments%0a%0a%0a%0a(:section: C:)%0a(:Category: LinguisticDiscriminationInTheWild:)
