diff:1620491223:1619496327:=87,101d86%0a%3c #foxbegin 210508-162703-989280#%0a%3c (:div1 class=expansionhead:)%0a%3c !!!Personal Experiences with Valley Girl Speak %0a%3c -> - dhrutik%0a%3c (:div1end:) %0a%3c >>messageitem%3c%3c %0a%3c I fully agree with the author and the above expansion, particularly that discrimination/assumptions on the basis of something as superficial as speaking patterns are trite and, in this day and age, should be behind us. %0a%3c %0a%3c The jokes that people make at the expense of "Valley girls" often remind me of the "Dumb blonde" stereotype. Both are used as a means to demean women and make them feel less than for something they can't really control.%0a%3c %0a%3c As someone from California, I have heard many people surprised to hear that I don't speak in the "Valley girl" way. The kicker is, I actually did live in the Valley until I started grade school. I think there is something interesting in terms of the "Valley girl" modality, particularly with respect to immigrant families and a need to "feel American." %0a%3c %0a%3c My mom would always tell me that from ages 3-5, whenever we went to family parties with my family that lived further north, near the Bay, my aunts and uncles would always comment on how "American" my accent was. Though I have no recording of myself from this time, I can only imagine that I spoke more like a "Valley girl" than my cousins did, which is what likely contributed to this feeling. Years later, after moving away, when I met people that stayed in the Valley, I found myself thinking the same thing-- that they sounded far more American than I did. It is so disorienting to suddenly question your own American-ness based off of something as simple as a regional accent, but it is a thing and I'm not sure how to quantify it.%0a%3c >>%3c%3c%0a%3c #foxend 210508-162703-989280#%0a
